<subSubSection id="C880C00732AFD5B42AF43AC0DAECE689" pageId="0" pageNumber="299" type="description">
<paragraph id="777A3FF80C845061E4D42AE02DE2FA38" pageId="0" pageNumber="299">Diagnostic characters.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="EB8AF9ED44ABD7C58D56576AB96C774A" pageId="0" pageNumber="299">Meristics: D-XII, 21; P1-17; P2-I, 5; A-III, 8; C-18; LL-59; GR- 5 + 15.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D442761335D968886EBC3D61913B0CE8" pageId="0" pageNumber="299">
Body compressed; dorsal profile of head strongly convex. Small mouth with fleshy lips, moderately thick; chin with 6 pores and no median pit. Dorsal fin slightly notched. Caudal fin truncate. Scales ctenoid; absent in front of snout, lips, and chin. Color of body whitish to grayish ground color on most parts of body; contrasting with many large, irregularly rounded black spots on body, nape, and soft portions of median fins, and smaller black spots on head. Posterior edge of opercle slightly serrate, margin of subopercle and interopercle smooth (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="C0418630BFCAEF10D4810F8E1C2936E1" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Lateral view of collected specimen, a. Plectorhinchus pictus, subspecies Plectorhinchus pictus cinerascens (F 1804 SM- 22; 105 SL mm), striped juvenile phase; b. Plectorhinchus macrospilus (F 1803 SM- 67; 335 mm SL); c. Plectorhinchus andamanensis, (F 1803 SM- 19; 137 mm SL); d. Pomadasys argenteus (F 1602 Sb- 01; 132 mm SL)." figureDoi="10.3897/aiep.51.67043.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/587693" pageId="0" pageNumber="299">2b</figureCitation>
). Lateral line continuous. Meristic measurements are given in Table 
<tableCitation id="ECECDB1B676A76B82102EA8C98B373EF" captionStart="Table 1" captionStartId="T1" captionText="Table 1. Meristic counts of the two new records of Plectorhinchus macrospilus and Pomadasys guoraca collected in the presently reported study, compared with reference data." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/7466B31DBFFE4689416A08A500E49321" pageId="0" pageNumber="299" tableUuid="7466B31DBFFE4689416A08A500E49321">1</tableCitation>
and Table 
<tableCitation id="F865EAF033C9BF296D5260B1D9EDC56D" captionStart="Table 2" captionStartId="T2" captionText="Table 2. Morphometric measurements of two new records of Plectorhinchus macrospilus and Pomadasys guoraca collected in the presently reported study." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/121CFA9653114D9FD9937C61FE269858" pageId="0" pageNumber="299" tableUuid="121CFA9653114D9FD9937C61FE269858">2</tableCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="4665EEBD34765170C2628EA71923591C" pageId="0" pageNumber="299" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="AFA714B0D7230E99F5DC63DC45A1E1FC" pageId="0" pageNumber="299">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8309E20953A5D9E7586E4C2F315C1157" pageId="0" pageNumber="299">
<taxonomicName id="E603CF5744AEBC685EA265C6B7047FF0" authorityName="Satapoomin et Randall" authorityYear="2000" class="Actinopterygii" family="Haemulidae" genus="Plectorhinchus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Plectorhinchus macrospilus" order="Perciformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="299" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macrospilus">
<emphasis id="F69226447EA570F8AE60F277567FD580" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="299">Plectorhinchus macrospilus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is one of six species of its genus that have numerous dark spots in adults; others are 
<taxonomicName id="E5E43881EC014604762A6958D3181718" authorityName="Lacepede" authorityYear="1801" class="Actinopterygii" family="Haemulidae" genus="Plectorhinchus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Plectorhinchus chaetodonoides" order="Perciformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="299" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="chaetodonoides">
<emphasis id="DF999169D6C7970FFC65B082A8925E3B" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="299">Plectorhinchus chaetodonoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; 
<taxonomicName id="39337F6CFB423DF9DA4F82AFEB0689F5" baseAuthorityName="Forsskal" baseAuthorityYear="1775" class="Actinopterygii" family="Haemulidae" genus="Plectorhinchus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Plectorhinchus gaterinus" order="Perciformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="299" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="gaterinus">
<emphasis id="92BCFCD4E01A69E2D71F06ABF5A65B30" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="299">Plectorhinchus gaterinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<normalizedToken id="15A782D2BCBD162A34E9FD7A85B3C87F" originalValue="Forsskål">Forsskal</normalizedToken>
, 1775); 
<taxonomicName id="EE4A51DDAF6E7FEFF878FFECA6526D87" baseAuthorityName="Cuvier" baseAuthorityYear="1828" class="Actinopterygii" family="Haemulidae" genus="Plectorhinchus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Plectorhinchus picus" order="Perciformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="299" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="picus">
<emphasis id="088011B7B886C9093445F0C03687DC7A" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="299">Plectorhinchus picus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Cuvier, 1828); 
<taxonomicName id="B67A032C478A1D50D4856F2CAFE0B560" baseAuthorityName="Thunberg" baseAuthorityYear="1792" class="Actinopterygii" family="Haemulidae" genus="Plectorhinchus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Plectorhinchus pictus" order="Perciformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="299" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pictus">
<emphasis id="133748BF548D04D67EBB5B6583879772" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="299">Plectorhinchus pictus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Thunberg, 1792); and 
<taxonomicName id="1AD382458F7D5823803AB2A0D4674995" baseAuthorityName="Temminck &amp; Schlegel" baseAuthorityYear="1843" class="Actinopterygii" family="Haemulidae" genus="Plectorhinchus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Plectorhinchus cinctus" order="Perciformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="299" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="cinctus">
<emphasis id="2C8A69D630E2D8E572B49DF505B8B860" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="299">Plectorhinchus cinctus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Temminck et Schlegel, 1843). The dark spots of 
<taxonomicName id="DDF578B1DFE76ED28FACCDB6E5EF7DB0" genus="P." lsidName="P. macrospilus" pageId="0" pageNumber="299" rank="species" species="macrospilus">
<emphasis id="D00214E6D90417AF56E18D660D24752C" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="299">P. macrospilus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are generally larger than those of the other five species, and 
<taxonomicName id="0AD2129012FCB9050AA8EB39E449E8A3" genus="P." lsidName="P. macrospilus" pageId="0" pageNumber="299" rank="species" species="macrospilus">
<emphasis id="E293D39CC2D9871A1297A82ACC08E110" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="299">P. macrospilus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
also has greater number of dorsal soft rays (21 vs. 15-20 for other species). Subadult 
<taxonomicName id="307CEFA0EE6195725B1C1C71EA8B1DB8" genus="P." lsidName="P. chaetodonoides" pageId="0" pageNumber="299" rank="species" species="chaetodonoides">
<emphasis id="A7293428FF466E10A0FFDB10370F814E" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="299">P. chaetodonoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are similar in coloration to 
<taxonomicName id="4AEFBD3C8201A8ABB88651496189C687" genus="P." lsidName="P. macrospilus" pageId="0" pageNumber="299" rank="species" species="macrospilus">
<emphasis id="C02A6D013FCA530961375F2A8A8B22DA" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="299">P. macrospilus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but are easily distinguished by gill raker count (9-12 + 28-33 versus 5 + 15 for 
<taxonomicName id="D8DAF961FBEAECF69056096CF74C9DE0" genus="P." lsidName="P. macrospilus" pageId="0" pageNumber="299" rank="species" species="macrospilus">
<emphasis id="BE0909A3B1186BA5C38730AAF4B17115" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="299">P. macrospilus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="BACA20572AB43D38D3819EC6E4D0CD78" pageId="0" pageNumber="299" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="9E6B5EAE712913196B613E6CDB92CBC9" pageId="0" pageNumber="299">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0E45ED1427DF1EF7BD5E4C9FD2BAD708" pageId="0" pageNumber="299">
<taxonomicName id="828F90F13386EE611F2F749A7F8AE84A" authorityName="Satapoomin et Randall" authorityYear="2000" class="Actinopterygii" family="Haemulidae" genus="Plectorhinchus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Plectorhinchus macrospilus" order="Perciformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="299" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macrospilus">
<emphasis id="0EE644EEA388736C9713D59A614A0560" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="299">Plectorhinchus macrospilus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known to occur from Thailand (
<bibRefCitation id="18539C2D81E568F4713B9F5473099235" author="Satapoomin, U" journalOrPublisher="Zootaxa" pageId="0" pageNumber="299" refId="B42" refString="Satapoomin, U, Randall, JE, 2000. Plectorhinchus macrospilus, a new species of thicklip (Perciformes: Haemulidae) from the Andaman Sea off southwestern Thailand. Phuket Marine Biological Center Research Bulletin, Thailand." title="Plectorhinchus macrospilus, a new species of thicklip (Perciformes: Haemulidae) from the Andaman Sea off southwestern Thailand. Phuket Marine Biological Center Research Bulletin, Thailand." year="2000">Satapoomin and Randall 2000</bibRefCitation>
) and Myanmar (Yangoon and Myiek Archipelago) (
<bibRefCitation id="C91FCC935B79C9987B423B0CB8159A51" author="Allen, GR" pageId="0" pageNumber="299" refId="B2" refString="Allen, GR, Erdmann, MV, 2012. Reef fishes of the East Indies. Volumes I-III. Tropical Reef Research. University of Hawai'i Press, Perth, Australia." title="Reef fishes of the East Indies. Volumes I-III. Tropical Reef Research. University of Hawai'i Press, Perth, Australia." year="2012">Allen and Erdmann 2012</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="885EE5728CDED486A2D5728624EFBBE7" author="Russell, BC" journalOrPublisher="FFI, Yangon" pageId="0" pageNumber="299" refId="B40" refString="Russell, BC, 2016. 2016 Survey of coral reef fishes of the Myeik Archipelago, Myanmar. Report No. 38 of the Tanintharyi Conservation Programme, a joint initiative of Fauna and Flora International (FFI) and the Myanmar Forest and Fisheries Departments. FFI, Yangon" title="2016 Survey of coral reef fishes of the Myeik Archipelago, Myanmar. Report No. 38 of the Tanintharyi Conservation Programme, a joint initiative of Fauna and Flora International (FFI) and the Myanmar Forest and Fisheries Departments." year="2016">Russell 2016</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="CCE6F3FD26DA7A8BCDE8CE571B82C0E6" author="Psomadakis, PN" journalOrPublisher="FAO, Rome and Ministry of Agriculture Livestock and Irrigation, Naypyitaw" pageId="0" pageNumber="299" refId="B33" refString="Psomadakis, PN, Thein, H, Russell, BC, Tun, MT, 2019. Field identification guide to the living marine resources of Myanmar. FAO Species Identification Guide for Fishery Purposes. FAO, Rome and Ministry of Agriculture Livestock and Irrigation, Naypyitaw" title="Field identification guide to the living marine resources of Myanmar. FAO Species Identification Guide for Fishery Purposes." year="2019">Psomadakis et al. 2019</bibRefCitation>
). This study confirms its occurrence also in the northern Bay of Bengal.
</paragraph>
